        "user": "How does \"token substrate\" differ from context window?",
        "assistant": "# Token Substrate vs. Context Window\n\nThese two concepts operate at very different levels of a language model's architecture. Here's how they compare:\n\n## Token Substrate (Recap)\n\nThe **token substrate** refers to the **underlying representational foundation** of individual tokens — the raw symbolic/structural layer before or beneath learned vector representations. It's about *what a token is* at its base level:\n\n- Token IDs from the vocabulary\n- Subword/byte-level encoding scheme\n- Associated metadata (position, type, etc.)\n- The \"substrate\" on which embeddings are built\n\n## Context Window\n\nThe **context window** is the **maximum span of tokens** a model can process or \"see\" at one time during inference or training. Key properties:\n\n- Measured in **number of tokens** (e.g., 4K, 8K, 128K, 1M tokens)\n- Defines the model's **working memory** for a single forward pass\n- Determined by architectural choices (attention mechanism, positional encoding scheme, compute/memory limits)\n- Tokens outside the window are **invisible** to the model in that pass\n\n## Key Differences\n\n| Aspect | Token Substrate | Context Window |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Scale** | Per-token (individual) | Sequence-level (collective) |\n| **Nature** | Representational foundation | Capacity/scope constraint |\n| **Measured in** | Features, IDs, structure | Number of tokens |\n| **Concerns** | *What* a token is | *How many* tokens fit |\n| **Set by** | Tokenizer + architecture | Model architecture/training |\n| **Analogy** | The material a brick is made of | The size of the wall you can build |\n\n## Analogy\n\nImagine reading a book:\n\n- **Token substrate** = the **letters and words** themselves — the raw symbols printed on the page, their fonts, their encoding.\n- **Context window** = how many **pages you can hold open and read simultaneously** before you have to close some and forget them.\n- **Embedding space** (from before) = the **mental understanding** you build of what those words mean and how they relate.\n\n## How They Interact\n\n1. Raw text is **tokenized** → producing tokens with their **substrate** properties (IDs, positions)\n2. Tokens are **embedded** → projected into the embedding space\n3. A sequence of these embeddings, up to the **context window** size, is fed into the model\n4. The model attends across all tokens *within the window* to generate output\n\nSo the substrate describes **individual tokens**, while the context window describes **how many of those tokens can be processed together**.\n\n## Same Caveat as Before\n\nAs I mentioned previously, **\"token substrate\" isn't a standardized term** in mainstream NLP. \"Context window,\" by contrast, is a well-established concept. If you're encountering \"token substrate\" in a specific source, sharing that context would help me align my explanation with the author's intended meaning.",
